<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - opinion]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/opinion <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/opinion" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - opinion - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 9 日星期三 01:09:33 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Another Biden Speech in Need of Clarification]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>限制核电站的燃料不会减少温室气体的排放。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590138690313713962"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590138690313713962"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-freeman"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BG857_freema_AM_20180731103058.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-freeman" itemprop="url" rel="author">詹姆斯·弗里曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日晚上 7:16 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/another-biden-speech-in-need-of-clarification-6ddd517f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832120?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">总统乔·拜登周二出现在亚利桑那州图萨扬以南的红山机场。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：吉姆·沃森/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>众所周知，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">乔·拜登</a>总统在偏离脚本言论时会陷入麻烦，但这并不能解释他周二在亚利桑那州发表的讲话中所蕴含的混乱。</p><p> Chris Megerian 和 Terry Tang <a href="https://apnews.com/article/grand-canyon-national-monument-biden-9382960f18408dce7aec52f103404e11" target="_blank" class="icon none">在大峡谷国家公园为美联社报道：</a></p><blockquote>总统乔·拜登周二签署了大峡谷国家纪念碑称号，宣称这“不仅对亚利桑那州而且对地球都有好处”，将美国原住民部落和环保主义者数十年的愿景变成了现实......</blockquote><blockquote>拜登说：“保护这些土地不仅对亚利桑那州而且对整个地球都有好处。”他的讲话背后是山景，他使用手持麦克风来抵御风，并戴着棒球帽和太阳镜来遮挡阳光。 ..</blockquote><blockquote>总统将这一指定与其政府应对气候变化的更大努力联系在一起，并指出今年夏天的极端炎热，这对凤凰城等地尤其造成了影响。他表示，与洪水和飓风等其他自然灾害相比，极端高温造成的死亡人数更多，但他补充说，“这一切都不一定是不可避免的。”</blockquote><p>不，事实并非如此。保护自己免受亚利桑那州夏季阳光的影响似乎是足够明智的。令人困惑的是，总统锁定了近一百万英亩土地，其主要结果是限制该地区潜在的铀矿开采。铀为核能提供燃料，这是一种罕见的技术，可以有效地产生大量能源，同时实现零温室气体排放。有了这个称号，他只是让实现自己的气候目标变得更加困难，但似乎给人的印象是他做了相反的事情。</p><p>人们可能会认为总统决定在错误的时刻重复他的气候谈话要点，或者可能是一名暑期实习生在提词器中加载了错误的演讲。但这似乎一直是白宫的计划——而这一次，拜登的下属似乎和他一样困惑。</p><p>在周一乘坐空军一号飞往亚利桑那州的航班上，白宫新闻秘书卡琳·让-皮埃尔采取了同样的方式，将政府零排放能源的新障碍描述为某种气候倡议。</p><p>让-皮埃尔女士说：“拜登总统继续将应对气候危机作为其总统任期的核心宗旨。”她随后向记者介绍了总统助理兼国家气候顾问阿里·扎伊迪。让-皮埃尔女士表示，扎伊迪先生“来这里是为了分享更多有关总统气候议程和我们即将前往的行程的信息。”</p><p>根据白宫的<a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/press-briefings/2023/08/07/press-gaggle-by-press-secretary-karine-jean-pierre-and-national-climate-advisor-ali-zaidi-en-route-grand-canyon-village-az/" target="_blank" class="icon none">文字记录</a>，他是这样说的：</p><blockquote>伟大的。正如卡琳所说，总统一直致力于对气候危机采取全政府应对措施。我们每天都会看到社区受到的影响。尤其是西方国家，首当其冲，热浪覆盖社区，天空变成橙色。</blockquote><blockquote>但这场危机也为我们提供了一个机会，让我们团结起来，推进我们的保护议程，并激发国内制造业的复兴。总统的此行将展示他是如何做到这一点的。</blockquote><blockquote>明天，他将宣布他的第五座新国家纪念碑。占地近100万英亩。人们都知道大峡谷沿岸有 3 亿年历史的悬崖。鲜为人知的是该地区有 300 处文化遗址。它们讲述了一段丰富而重要的历史。这也是 12 个部落站出来要求宣布这座纪念碑的原因。总统将采取行动来做到这一点。</blockquote><p>如果没有气候顾问也愿意分享他们丰富的文化历史方面的专业知识，我们该怎么办？人们不禁想起公共卫生专家，他们在新冠恐慌期间暂时放弃了对不戴口罩集会的反对，转而支持左翼政治抗议。</p><p>如果总统的气候顾问也承认其他优先事项，也许选民会放心，所谓的气候危机不会那么严重。一个合理的结论是，如果连白宫气候办公室都不想在追求减排方面走得太远，那么“全政府的应对措施”就几乎没有必要。</p><p>但显然，潜在的铀矿开采损失并不是总统行动的唯一问题。在盐湖论坛报马克·爱丁顿<a href="https://www.sltrib.com/news/politics/2023/08/08/bidens-new-arizona-national/" target="_blank" class="icon none">报道</a>中：</p><blockquote>卡纳布市议会议员、第六代牧场主克里斯·希顿 (Chris Heaton) 尤其担心，他在亚利桑那州大道拥有或租赁的约 48,000 英亩土地上放牧着 200 头牛。他说这座纪念碑包括他 1000 英亩的私人财产……</blockquote><blockquote> “自从我们来到这里以来，牧场主就一直在使用这片土地，我们做得非常好，”希顿说。 “这就是[联邦政府]想要它的原因，因为他们认为他们比我们能更好地管理它。”</blockquote><blockquote>希顿还称，国家纪念碑将保护原住民文化和圣地的想法只是烟幕弹，因为政府将通过广告吸引成千上万的人来到该地区，这将导致这片土地被涂鸦和人类排泄物所亵渎。</blockquote><p> ***</p><p>也许白宫气候办公室应该从对文化宝藏的深入研究中抽出时间来注意到，除了核电之外，零排放能源运动并没有真正蓬勃发展。 《华尔街日报》的 Mari Novik 和 Jennifer Hiller <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wind-industry-hits-rough-seas-as-problems-mount-5490403a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">报道</a>：</p><blockquote>各国政府认为风电业务是实现气候目标和增加电力供应的关键，但它正面临着危险的市场风暴。</blockquote><blockquote>经过数月关于价格上涨和物流问题的警告后，风电开发商和潜在买家正在取消合同、推迟项目并推迟投资决策。陆上和海上项目都遇到了越来越多的挫折，但后者的问题更为严重。</blockquote><blockquote>最近几周，美国和欧洲至少有 10 个总计划支出约 330 亿美元的离岸项目被推迟或陷入低迷。</blockquote><p> ***</p><p><em>詹姆斯·弗里曼是<a href="https://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1982163984" target="_blank" class="icon none">《成本：特朗普、中国和美国复兴》一书</a>的合著者，也是<a href="https://www.amazon.com/Borrowed-Time-Centuries-Booms-Bailouts/dp/0062669877/ref=asc_df_0062669877/?tag=hyprod-20&amp;linkCode=df0&amp;hvadid=312143020546&amp;hvpos=&amp;hvnetw=g&amp;hvrand=10412016619786864649&amp;hvpone=&amp;hvptwo=&amp;hvqmt=&amp;hvdev=c&amp;hvdvcmdl=&amp;hvlocint=&amp;hvlocphy=9003741&amp;hvtargid=pla-525185269824&amp;psc=1" target="_blank" class="icon none">《借来的时间：花旗两个世纪的繁荣、萧条和救助》一书的合著者。</a></em></p><p> ***</p><p>在<a href="https://twitter.com/FreemanWSJ" target="_blank" class="icon none">Twitter</a>上关注詹姆斯·弗里曼。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?sub=157&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">订阅最佳网络电子邮件。</a></p><p>如需推荐商品，请发送电子邮件至 best@wsj.com。</p><p> （特蕾莎·沃佐 (Teresa Vozzo) 帮助编译了最佳网络奖。）</p><p> ***</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 23:16:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/another-biden-speech-in-need-of-clarification-6ddd517f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/another-biden-speech-in-need-of-clarification-6ddd517f<author><![CDATA[James Freeman]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球/世界问题</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>乔·拜登</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球的</category><category>世界问题</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Washington Stages a Peacetime Fiscal Blowout]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>联邦债务利息已达到联邦收入的 15.5%。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590138513637661190"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590138513637661190"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日下午 6:37 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-stages-a-peacetime-fiscal-blowout-3ba548d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832159?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：Getty Images/iStockphoto</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>以一种反常的方式祝贺拜登总统和他的国会同志们。最新的预算数据显示，他们正在打破和平时期、非危机时期的支出和赤字记录。而且看不到任何喘息的机会。</p><p>根据国会预算办公室 7 月份的月度审查，环城公路兄弟在本财年的前 10 个月累计赤字达 1.62 万亿美元。这一数字高于一年前的 7,260 亿美元。 CBO 表示，如果不是部分付款日期发生变化，赤字将会更高，达到 1.7 万亿美元，即增加 131%。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>令人震惊的是，环城公路的井喷发生在经济增长、新冠危机已经过去、而且没有国内紧急情况需要解决的情况下。这是赤字应该下降的时期，就像 20 世纪 80 年代、1990 年代和 2000 年代经济扩张期间那样。 2010年共和党重新控制众议院后，奥巴马总统领导下的赤字也有所下降。</p><p> CBO 列出了血淋淋的细节。尽管民主党提高了公司税，但收入仍下降了约 10%。个人所得税收入下降 20%，即约 4,420 亿美元，CBO 推测原因之一是资本收益变现减少。当富人不在金融市场上赚钱时，浸泡富人是行不通的。</p><p>今年到目前为止，支出增长了 11%，即 4,730 亿美元，如果不改变付款时间，支出可能会更高，达到 5,360 亿美元。支出低谷包括拜登最新的学生贷款不偿还计划增加了 710 亿美元；社会保障增加 1,110 亿美元，主要用于通货膨胀的生活成本调整；更高的支付率和更多的护理将为医疗保险带来 1,040 亿美元的收入。</p><p>纳税人还为硅谷银行和其他银行的春季救助提供了 520 亿美元。国会预算办公室表示，财政部将从资产清算和更高的存款保险保费中收回大部分资金。但如果拜登监管机构没有如此挑剔地允许哪些机构竞购破产银行，那么这些破产事件的代价就不会那么大。</p><p>今年迄今为止支出增幅最大的是不断飙升的联邦债务的净利息：增加 1,460 亿美元至 5,720 亿美元，即 34%。这一利息总额几乎是今年迄今为止企业税收总额 3190 亿美元的两倍。</p><p>本财年的债务利息已攀升至所有联邦收入的 15.5%，而且截至 7 月的 10 个月中的大部分时间都远早于利率达到目前的水平。由于财政部计划在本财季以更高的利率发行 1 万亿美元新债，利息支付将继续飙升。拜登的支出狂潮才刚刚开始，需要更多的债务来资助《减少通货膨胀法案》、《筹码法案》和基础设施法案。</p><p>无论以任何标准衡量，对于任何国家来说，这都是一场可怕的财政表现。下次美国财政部向希腊或意大利谈论他们的财政困境时，南欧人应该会大笑起来。</p><p>更令人沮丧的是，在威胁日益严重的世界中，不断扩大的赤字将使增加国防开支变得更加困难。学生贷款注销不会阻止中国入侵台湾或朝鲜导弹瞄准西雅图。</p><p>赤字还会使维持低税率以及在 2025 年到期时延长特朗普税率的情况变得更加复杂。更高的税收将降低为所有这些支出提供资金所需的经济增长。很少有总统的财政记录比<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">乔·拜登</a>更糟糕。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=EF98C809-AE43-4880-9FBD-64459B5B35BD&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwashington-stages-a-peacetime-fiscal-blowout-3ba548d&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊社论报告：如何使国会无效。图片：彭博新闻/美联社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 22:37:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-stages-a-peacetime-fiscal-blowout-3ba548d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/washington-stages-a-peacetime-fiscal-blowout-3ba548d<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算/税收</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>乔·拜登</category><category>政府财政</category><category>政府预算</category><category>税收</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Gift to Putin: No Uranium Mining Near the Grand Canyon]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>新政府的土地掠夺使美国更加依赖俄罗斯。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590138252945701556"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590138252945701556"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日下午 6:34 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-gift-to-putin-no-uranium-mining-near-the-grand-canyon-6c1916bf"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832157?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 8 月 8 日，乔·拜登总统在亚利桑那州图萨扬的红山机场举着指定 Baaj Nwaavjo I&#39;Tah Kukveni 国家纪念碑的公告。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：约翰·洛彻/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周二，拜登总统大笔一挥，封锁了近一百万英亩的土地，禁止开发，其中包括美国一些最丰富的铀矿床。这是政府破坏性能源政策的又一座纪念碑。</p><p> 1906 年的《古物法》允许总统留出联邦土地用于国家纪念碑，以保护历史文物。巴拉克·奥巴马(Barack Obama)利用该法律取消了数百万英亩的联邦土地用于石油和天然气开发。然而，就连他也抵制了在大峡谷外划出富含铀的土地的进步呼吁。拜登先生没有表现出这样的克制。</p><p>周二，他宣布在亚利桑那州 1,562 平方英里的土地上建立一座国家纪念碑，名为 Baaj Nwaavjo I&#39;tah Kukveni，意思是“部落漫游的地方”。白宫表示，这座纪念碑将保护“部落民族和原住民神圣的景观，并推进拜登总统的历史性气候和保护议程”。</p><p>该声明忽略了这片土地还包括美国唯一在全球市场上具有经济竞争力的高品位铀矿石来源。美国约95%用于核反应堆的铀进口，主要来自哈萨克斯坦、加拿大、俄罗斯和澳大利亚。俄罗斯是美国第三大铀来源国。</p><p>去年春天，拜登通过行政命令禁止进口俄罗斯化石燃料，但美国核电站 12% 的燃料供应仍依赖俄罗斯铀。新的国家纪念碑——拜登总统任期内的第五座纪念碑——将使美国更难取代俄罗斯的铀矿。<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>致谢。</p><p>国家纪念碑未说明的目的似乎是阻止铀矿开采。亚利桑那州民主党众议员劳尔·格里哈尔瓦 (Raul Grijalva) 提出立法，永久将大峡谷地区从新的采矿权中撤回。民主党无法在国会通过这项法案，因此拜登先生通过法令这样做了。</p><p>部落声称铀矿开采可能会污染水和野生动物。但 2021 年美国地质调查局发现，尽管进行了数十年的铀矿开采，该地区的泉水和水井仍符合联邦饮用水标准。拜登总统似乎并不认为可以同时开发和保护美国的自然资源，尽管矿商几十年来一直在这样做。</p><p>进步人士希望阻止美国的所有采矿活动，包括推动绿色能源转型所需的锂和镍等关键矿物的开采。但这意味着采矿将发生在环境保护较少的国家。</p><p>目前，根据《古物法》，总统将土地从开发和公共用途中移除的权力没有任何限制。环保组织甚至认为总统不能撤销前任的任命。这种对单向行政权力的解释比大峡谷更为广泛，并且迫切需要法律挑战。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B0B49BB4-E58D-4FC7-A236-C7F1046D346E&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fa-gift-to-putin-no-uranium-mining-near-the-grand-canyon-6c1916bf&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">回顾与展望：阿留申群岛附近的联合海军巡逻是对美国的警告和考验 图片：祖马出版社/阿拉斯加火山观测站/美联社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 22:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-gift-to-putin-no-uranium-mining-near-the-grand-canyon-6c1916bf</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-gift-to-putin-no-uranium-mining-near-the-grand-canyon-6c1916bf<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>活力</category><category>金属矿石开采</category><category>基本材料/资源</category><category>采矿/采石</category><category>有色金属矿开采</category><category>铀矿开采</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>土地利用</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>土地利用</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>地区政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>活力</category><category>金属矿石开采</category><category>基础材料</category><category>资源</category><category>矿业</category><category>采石</category><category>有色金属矿开采</category><category>铀矿开采</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Judicial Politicians of Wisconsin]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>州最高法院新的进步多数从首席大法官手中夺取了权力。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590136662468101230"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590136662468101230"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日下午 6:32 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-judicial-politicians-of-wisconsin-6dfb3b36"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831343?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">位于麦迪逊的威斯康星州议会大厦。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：斯科特·鲍尔/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>要了解法官政治化后会发生什么，请看一下威斯康星州新的进步最高法院多数派。上周，随着新任大法官珍妮特·普罗塔谢维奇（Janet Protasiewicz）的上任，他们以 4 比 3 成为多数派，他们的第一个行动就是一场行政政变。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>周五，四名自由派人士对法庭程序进行了修改，使他们能够篡夺首席大法官的权力，包括控制口头辩论、规则听证会和行政会议的日程。他们还发布了一项新规则，要求在多数意见形成后 7 天内提出异议。</p><p>为什么这么快就行使权力，而且没有通常的司法合议？也许是因为控制司法日历就意味着控制政治日历。</p><p>法院可能很快就会听到对该州立法地图的质疑，普罗塔谢维奇法官今年竞选最高法院席位时称这些地图“被操纵”。将异议写作限制在 7 天内将加快裁决的时间表，并让保守派有更少的时间来整理他们的论点。想象一下，如果六名保守派大法官在美国最高法院施展这一伎俩，将会引发怎样的轩然大波。</p><p>国家党和威斯康星州民主党长期以来一直想推翻该州的立法地图，现在他们正在提高出价。竞选法律中心、Law Forward、哈佛大学选举法诊所和其他团体正在要求威斯康星州法院推翻立法地图，并发布“令状<em>保证书</em>”，要求所有州立法者，包括 2022 年 11 月当选的议员，参加竞选再次在新划定的地区。</p><p>威斯康星州最高法院最初批准了州长托尼·埃弗斯 (Tony Evers) 绘制的地图，并于 2022 年批准了当前的威斯康星州立法地图。当埃弗斯地图被美国最高法院推翻后，法院批准了目前由共和党立法机构绘制的地图。</p><p>但请愿者仍然指望他们帮助选出的新自由派法院多数派能够很快推翻地图。在“违宪配置的选区”举行的选举。请愿书称，应宣布“非法”，法院应“下令在 2024 年 11 月为所有人举行特别选举……”。 。 。州参议院选区要到 2026 年 11 月才会出现这种情况。”</p><p>请愿者建议最高法院在 2024 年 3 月 19 日之前发布裁决，这也就不足为奇了：2024 年 11 月选举的提名文件将于 4 月 15 日开始散发。</p><p>翻译：法院越早扔掉地图，民主党就能越早选出新的进步立法机构。目标是翻转足够的席位，在威斯康星州建立新的民主党立法多数。这将有助于埃弗斯推翻前州长斯科特·沃克（Scott Walker）的集体谈判改革（即第 10 号法案），并终止威斯康星州的择校计划。</p><p>威斯康星州宪法规定，州最高法院首席大法官“应是司法系统的行政首长”。现任首席大法官安妮特·齐格勒 (Annette Ziegler) 称新自由派多数派的改革是“试图削弱首席大法官作为法院管理者的宪法权威”。听起来不错。进步四人并不担心自己的政治形象，因为他们竞相将獾州变成明尼苏达州或伊利诺伊州。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F39EC653-A48E-4FB7-AF6D-1F040C95B008&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-judicial-politicians-of-wisconsin-6dfb3b36&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊社论报告：Kim Strassel、Kyle Peterson、Kate Bachelder 和 Dan Henninger 的本周最佳和最差图片：路透社/美联社综合报道：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 22:32:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-judicial-politicians-of-wisconsin-6dfb3b36</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-judicial-politicians-of-wisconsin-6dfb3b36<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Fix the Court’ Should Fix Itself]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>左翼组织可能违反了 501(c)3 披露规则。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590136000500985346"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590136000500985346"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日下午 6:31 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fix-the-court-should-fix-itself-788170d8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832191?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">文件 - 2017 年 10 月 10 日日落时分看到的华盛顿最高法院。（美联社照片/J. Scott Applewhite，文件）</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：J. Scott Applewhite/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>如果那些攻击最高法院法官涉嫌道德过失的进步人士能够言出必行，那就太好了。以“修复法院”组织为例，该组织正在与民主党合作，通过法官的道德和信息披露规则，同时忽视披露其游说活动的要求。</p><p> Fix the Court 正在领导一场针对克拉伦斯·托马斯 (Clarence Thomas) 和塞缪尔·阿利托 (Samuel Alito) 法官的运动，他们涉嫌与亿万富翁有联系。该非营利组织是新风险基金的一个分支，该基金是由左翼营利性阿拉贝拉顾问公司支持的进步团体网络之一。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “我们是全国唯一致力于通过倡导一些简单的‘修复’来开放政府最强大、最不负责任的部分——最高法院的团体，”修复法院的网站称。 “修复”意味着减少保守派对最高法院的影响。</p><p>其中一项解决方案是参议员谢尔登·怀特豪斯 (Sheldon Whitehouse) 的《最高法院道德、回避和透明度法案》。上个月，“修复法院”执行董事加布·罗斯出现在怀特豪斯先生的播客中，“讨论如何通过立法加强法院的道德护栏”。</p><p>怀特豪斯的法案将根据国会的现行规则，为法院制定“礼物、收入和报销”的披露规则。它还将任命来自巡回上诉法院的五名首席法官组成的小组，负责听取来自 Fix the Court 等团体针对法官的道德投诉。由三名法官组成的小组将审查各方提出的回避“动议”。</p><p>目的是将道德和信息披露武器化。进步人士希望对保守派大法官提出道德指控，无论这些指控多么毫无根据，以损害他们的声誉并迫使他们回避重要案件。</p><p>然而，正如《华盛顿观察报》最近报道的那样，Fix the Court 并未遵守其应遵守的披露规则。作为 501(c)(3) 公共慈善机构，该机构可以隐藏其捐赠者的姓名。捐款还可免税。但慈善机构必须遵守政治活动的限制。</p><p>美国国税局网站指出，“如果组织的大部分活动试图影响立法（通常称为游说），则任何组织都没有资格获得第 501(c)(3) 条的资格”，其中包括敦促“公众联系、立法机构的成员或雇员”并主张“通过或否决立法”。 IRS 将“大部分”定义为支出的 20% 以上。</p><p>慈善机构必须在其 990 纳税申报表上披露是否参与政治游说。Fix 法院声称其没有就 2022 年公开披露进行游说。然而，其网站上列出了一长串其支持或反对的司法法案。</p><p>它还表示，它正在“在第 118 届国会中与议员合作，敦促司法部门采用国会议员和高级行政部门官员必须遵守的同样严格的旅行、礼品和个人招待规则”，并支持国会利用其法定权力“迫使人们接受[道德]准则。”根据国税局的定义，这看起来确实像是政治游说。</p><p>当审查员要求发表评论时，法院没有回应。为了回应我们的询问，该公司董事会主席乔什·科恩发表了一份声明：</p><p> “Gabe [Roth] 和 Fix the Court 一直秉持诚信行事，当我们意识到 990 不完整时，我们就开始努力纠正它。在党派偏见占主导地位的时刻，修复最高法院是非常无党派的，它继续要求民主党和共和党总统提名的法官遵循最高的道德标准——这与我们对其他两个分支的要求相同。”</p><p>换句话说，该组织谴责大法官披露错误，但当它因同样的事情而受到指责时，它声称自己的行为是“善意的”。也许修复法院应该首先用民主党参议员的话说，在国会或国税局要求其重组之前“自我治愈”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=BA8E58C2-9DA6-441F-8E2E-AC81AF123818&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffix-the-court-should-fix-itself-788170d8&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊社论报告：一场包装和期限限制的运动出现。图片：法新社/盖蒂图片社/美联社综合报道：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">《华尔街日报》互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 22:31:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fix-the-court-should-fix-itself-788170d8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fix-the-court-should-fix-itself-788170d8<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>突击</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>伦理道德问题</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>突击</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>伦理道德问题</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>社会问题</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Impeaching a Trump Impeachment]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>亨特·拜登的新细节证明了 2019 年臭名昭著的乌克兰通话的合理性。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590137861336404060"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11380450262913973852004590137861336404060"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/holman-w-jenkinsjr"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BI571_jenkin_AM_20180807123815.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline">作者：<span class="author" itemprop="name">小</span><span class="author" itemprop="name">霍尔曼·W·詹金斯</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日下午 6:20 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/impeaching-a-trump-impeachment-hunter-biden-partisan-investigation-ukraine-gop-election-847d972"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831862?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 8 月 5 日，前总统唐纳德·特朗普在南卡罗来纳州哥伦比亚。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Artie Walker Jr./美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>让党派的唾沫飞扬吧，就像第一次弹劾特朗普时那样。谁在 2016 年解雇了乌克兰总检察长？原因为何？由于前亨特·拜登合伙人德文·阿彻在国会的证词，这个问题又回来了。</p><p>无论发生什么，事情都不是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>所说的那样。这也不是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">乔·拜登</a>所说的那样。他声称安排解雇检察官维克多·肖金，并向时任总统彼得·波罗申科发出最后通牒，这只是乔的又一个荒诞故事。几个月后，在几个西方政府的要求下，肖金被解职。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>但阿彻先生的证词驳斥了特朗普支持者所讲述的简单故事，即肖金先生被解雇是为了保护乔和亨特·拜登。阿切尔表示，肖金之所以受到乌克兰领导层的重视，正是因为他隐瞒了对布里斯马公司的长期调查，亨特是一家天然气公司的董事会成员。</p><p>这<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-wrong-impeachers-11572649090?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">符合</a>我当时的看法。拜登先生不需要做任何事情。事实上，他可以与欧盟和其他捐助者一起对肖金采取反腐败姿态，因为他知道乌克兰完全有动力保护拜登家族。</p><p>不管解雇的原因是什么，肯定不是为了给布里斯马制造麻烦。</p><p>如果是这样，民主党现在只需为亨特的商业骗局辩护，正如党内政治专家所说，兜售“进入的幻觉”。乔只需去几家餐馆、用免提电话聊聊天气、借给亨特一些白宫、空军二号等的装饰，漫不经心地煽动这种幻觉，这都是可以原谅的。</p><p>也就是说，等待其他证据失败。阿彻先生说，至少有一次，Burisma 创始人米科拉·兹洛切夫斯基 (Mykola Zlochevsky) 在喝酒时敦促亨特代表他“给 DC 打电话”，亨特照做了。一名 FBI 线人称，兹洛切夫斯基声称曾对拜登夫妇的通话进行录音，并行贿 1000 万美元。笔记本电脑的证据也呈现出各种复杂性。</p><p>不过，我一直以来的假设是，当乔·拜登知道亨特无所事事就能榨取数百万美元时，他不会愚蠢到做任何事。</p><p>但司法部拖延税务调查，以允许因时效而撤销与亨特的布里斯马收入相关的指控，也存在政治风险。在亨特的几笔意外之财中，他在布里斯马的收入最直接地利用了他父亲的角色，最直接地与他父亲的具体行为（解雇肖金）联系在一起，并为特朗普先生的第一次弹劾辩护提供了最直接的证据，涉及他打电话给特朗普的弹劾调查。泽伦斯基总统正在寻找有关拜登在乌克兰交易的信息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>了解更多商业世界</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-doj-vs-doj-in-the-2024-race-hunter-joe-biden-trump-indictment-smith-429971ee?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">这是 2024 年选举中的 DOJ 与 DOJ 的较量</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 4 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ai-is-hollywoods-fake-villain-unions-strike-actors-writers-ai-jobs-studios-9cdb3ab4?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">人工智能是好莱坞的假恶棍</a><span class="date">2023 年 8 月 1 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-is-a-geopolitical-disaster-biden-plea-deal-russia-twitter-4f2653e6?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">亨特·拜登是一场地缘政治灾难</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 28 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>这里有一些新消息。特朗普先生很可能是从司法部长威廉·巴尔那里得知的</p>关于与联邦调查局交谈的布里斯马内部人士——这意味着特朗普先生既可以保守秘密，又可以为他向泽伦斯基先生提出的要求提供更坚实的基础，他在联邦调查局的一项调查中寻求合作，我们现在知道这项调查正在进行中机密线人的证词。<p></p><p>嗯。</p><p>白宫最新的辩护含蓄地承认乔可能与亨特讨论过业务，但他并没有与亨特“做生意”。如果事实表明乔做了一切事情来促进亨特的“进入幻觉”，除了出售官方行为或加入亨特的工资单之外，还有很大的回旋余地。</p><p>尽管如此，拜登先生还能连任吗？是的，就像特朗普先生可以从监狱中当选一样。不过，民主党圈子里一片沉默，因为这也增加了拜登“身体不适”而退出竞选的可能性。</p><p>有些人认为，司法部特别顾问杰克·史密斯不过是其他地方制定的一项政策决定的执行者，该决定已在《华盛顿邮报》上 <a href="https://twitter.com/mrddmia/status/1688319081383129088" target="_blank" class="icon none">电报</a>。</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NYT" class="company-name">《纽约时报》</a> ，2022 年 4 月，拜登先生对特朗普先生提出指控，作为其选举策略的一部分。<p></p><p>拜登先生与国家玩骰子，因为他认为特朗普先生是他可以击败的唯一一位共和党提名人。</p><p>佛罗里达州的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">罗恩·德桑蒂斯 (Ron DeSantis)</a>和加利福尼亚州的加文·纽瑟姆 (Gavin Newsom) 之间将举行电视辩论，选民心中燃起一丝希望，这或许会掀起 2024 年替代总统候选人<a href="https://www.tabletmag.com/sections/arts-letters/articles/david-garrow-interview-obama" target="_blank" class="icon none">名单</a>的热潮。奥巴马传记作者大卫·加罗 (David Garrow) 在《关注“诺贝尔奖”和马丁·路德·金传记的名气，将奥巴马式的犬儒主义问题摆上了桌面。乔·拜登让数百万选民相信他会免除他们的学生债务，尽管他知道自己做不到。拜登现在正在竭尽全力确保国家必须在他和特朗普之间做出选择。但许多失误都发生在嘴上——健康危机、亨特事件爆发、特朗普无罪释放、乌克兰局势逆转——这可能会让拜登和史密斯成为将白宫交给唐纳德·特朗普的人。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5DE7BC77-6402-4B80-A5E9-9E8AC3644D45&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fimpeaching-a-trump-impeachment-hunter-biden-partisan-investigation-ukraine-gop-election-847d972&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">杂志社论报道：司法部加速法律攻势。图片：Zuma Press/AFP/Getty Images 合成：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 22:20:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/impeaching-a-trump-impeachment-hunter-biden-partisan-investigation-ukraine-gop-election-847d972</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/impeaching-a-trump-impeachment-hunter-biden-partisan-investigation-ukraine-gop-election-847d972<category>弹劾</category><category>党派</category><category>总统</category><category>共和党</category><category>辩论</category><category>税务调查</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>见证</category><category>联邦调查局</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>弹劾</category><category>政治任命/终止</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>乔·拜登</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治任命</category><category>终止</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘In My Room’ on the Riverfront]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>沿着哈德逊河散步，我听到了海滩男孩的经典歌曲。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128440863742002"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128440863742002"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"><span class="author" itemprop="name">鲍勃·格林</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日下午 6:19 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-my-room-on-the-riverfront-music-beach-boys-lyrics-new-york-1c4841da"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831902?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 1964 年 11 月 1 日，布莱恩·威尔逊 (Brian Wilson) 在卢森堡的广播节目中。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：RB/Redferns</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>当我决定转向 45 号码头时，我正沿着曼哈顿下城的哈得逊河散步，这是一条可以让行人近距离接触河水的长廊。码头上有很多人，享受着夏日的周日下午。</p><p>在远处，我听到有人唱着我已经熟悉了 60 年的歌词：“有一个世界，我可以去那里，告诉我的秘密……” 。 。 ”</p><p>这是海滩男孩 1963 年的歌曲《In My Room》，其中布莱恩·威尔逊 (Brian Wilson) 纯净、年轻的声音讲述了一个在紧闭的门后寻找慰藉的令人难忘的故事。</p><p> “在这个世界上，我将所有的忧虑和恐惧拒之门外。 。 ”。</p><p>不过，我在 45 号码头听到的并不是威尔逊先生的声音。其他人正在演唱这首歌的现场版本。</p><p>一名 70 岁左右的非裔美国人独自坐在电子琴前。当他唱歌时，他没有面向内，面向在码头上行走的人们，而是面向外，面向河流本身。</p><p> 81 岁的威尔逊先生最近身体一直不好。他没有巡回演出或公开表演。喜欢他音乐的人都想念他。</p><p>这个人在码头上，对着水面唱歌。唱着布莱恩的声音赋予了一种不朽的歌词。我继续走，离开了码头，但很快决定绕回来和那个人谈谈。</p><p>他的名字叫丹尼尔·阿尔-马丁，</p>他今年 74 岁。他说，他喜欢演奏和唱歌，最喜欢的音乐类型是节奏蓝调音乐和雷鬼音乐。<p></p><p>我告诉他，作为布莱恩乐队成员的朋友，我知道布莱恩听到哈德逊河上的这次独奏表演会很高兴，而且我很确定我可以向他传达消息。但我有一个问题：为什么要在这个地方、在这一天选择“在我的房间里”？</p><p> Mr. Al-Mateen said he had been feeling especially wistful about all the losses in his life as the years have passed. His mother, gone. His father, gone. His brother, gone. His sister, gone. His best friends, gone. His wife, gone.</p><p> So he put his keyboard and a power pack into a shopping cart and wheeled it out to the end of the pier. “In My Room,” he had long thought, was “so beautiful, so poignant in its seeming simplicity.” He wanted to remind himself that “the people we have loved may have left us, but they are with us forever, every time we think about them.”</p><p> “Do my dreaming and my scheming, lie awake and pray / Do my crying and my sighing, laugh at yesterday . 。 .”</p><p> I asked him about the setting: Why, with the private thoughts that were filling him, had he left his own room to come sing “In My Room” to the river?</p><p> “You don&#39;t need a castle,” he said. “You just need a place where you can go to stay out of the maelstrom.”</p><p> I promised him I would find a way to let Brian know about his lovely rendition on this New York day.</p><p> “Please tell him thank you,” Mr. Al-Mateen said. “Please tell him thank you for everything.”</p><p> <em>Mr. Greene&#39;s books include “When We Get to Surf City: A Journey Through America in Pursuit of Rock and Roll, Friendship, and Dreams.”</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F39EC653-A48E-4FB7-AF6D-1F040C95B008&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fin-my-room-on-the-riverfront-music-beach-boys-lyrics-new-york-1c4841da&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Journal Editorial Report: The week&#39;s best and worst from Kim Strassel, Kyle Peterson, Kate Bachelder and Dan Henninger Images: Reuters/AP Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 22:19:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-my-room-on-the-riverfront-music-beach-boys-lyrics-new-york-1c4841da</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-my-room-on-the-riverfront-music-beach-boys-lyrics-new-york-1c4841da<category>音乐</category><category>new york</category><category> beach boys</category><category> sogn</category><category>生活</category><category>lyrics</category><category> immortality</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Recoding America’ Review: A Tale of the Tape]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The bigger obstacle to modernizing Washington and making government more efficient is politics, not bureaucratic red tape. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128081788835478"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831957?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Getty Images/iStockphoto </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590128081788835478"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Mark P. Mills</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 8, 2023 6:18 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/recoding-america-review-a-tale-of-the-tape-449e8b3c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Apparently the swamp in Washington, DC, is not a political but a bureaucratic mire. As Jennifer Pahlka writes in “Recoding America: Why Government Is Failing in the Digital Age and How We Can Do Better,” bureaucracy “bogs down our systems,” creating a chasm “between policy intentions and actual outcomes.” She believes we “desperately need to simplify and rationalize” it all because the bureaucratic “implementation crisis threatens our democracy.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/b2d574cb-e749-4c96-a034-7b43fc3c907f.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Given the allusion to computer code in her book&#39;s title, you&#39;d be forgiven for thinking that “Recoding America” is about algorithms and artificial intelligence put in the service of taming, not draining, the swamp. But the term “artificial intelligence” appears only twice here, both times to dismiss its relevance. While that omission may be refreshing in the wake of all the ChatGPT hype, it&#39;s also puzzling given how Ms. Pahlka asserts that our “digital age is different from previous eras.”</p><p> Among her many roles in government, Ms. Pahlka has served as President Barack Obama&#39;s deputy chief technology officer for government innovation. Most of her book is a chronicle of her experiences working on various task forces for President Obama and California&#39;s Gov. Gavin Newsom. There are her journeys through bureaucracies involving the reclassifying of criminal records that have been rendered moot by California&#39;s marijuana legalization; implementing ObamaCare; reforming the Veterans Administration; taming the Medicare morass; and, most recently, distributing California&#39;s gusher of Covid unemployment payments. Ms. Pahlka details the “messy task of [policy] implementation through digital technology,” as well as the challenges created by “archaeological” layers of legacy computer systems and bureaucratic processes that bog things down.</p><p> Ms. Pahlka saw firsthand the “gap between policy intentions and actual outcomes” and “the famous slowness of bureaucracy.” One cannot resist paraphrasing the author&#39;s former boss: “The 1300s are calling and they want their bureaucratic characterizations back.” In 1321, Dante, himself a Florentine bureaucrat, wrote “The Divine Comedy,” which frames Hell as the epitome of bureaucracy. And that was before the invention of the printing press and its epic contribution of paperwork. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831988?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Jennifer Pahlka</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Fisher Studios</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For those not steeped in the modern bureaucratic process and its intersection with the arcana of computer systems, Ms. Pahlka&#39;s clear, diarylike explanations of (and frustrations with) bureaucracy are illuminating. As she notes, it&#39;s a daunting task even to get an accurate count of the number of eligible recipients for government largess. While her concern for quickly and fairly delivering government services is universally shared, it&#39;s in the procedures used to get “the outcomes the democratic process has agreed upon” where we find the devil-in-the-details truism.</p><p> As advice for well-meaning bureaucrats, Ms. Pahlka admiringly quotes Gen. Stanley McChrystal&#39;s dictum: “Don&#39;t follow my orders, follow the orders I would have given you if I were there and knew what you know.” But that is precisely where the battles over bureaucratic authority are being fought. As Ms. Pahlka observes, Republicans are opposed to “federal activism” and look for “ways to curb the power” of agencies. Democrats, meanwhile, want “administrative agencies to be able to exercise their own judgment.” That&#39;s no mere detail; it&#39;s the essence of the political debate over the administrative state.</p><p> Ms. Pahlka sees two main problems with today&#39;s bureaucracy: a lack of sufficient “technological know-how” in the workforce, and too much outsourcing. “Why do we treat the experts we do have with so little regard?” Ms. Pahlka asks. “It wasn&#39;t always that way.” Indeed, that&#39;s the core of the debate of our times; serious tomes have been devoted to that question.</p><p> Ms. Pahlka&#39;s proffered solutions include improving the bureaucratic “culture” with more internal training programs, more tech talent and less outsourcing. She suggests that the government seek out the kind of young graduates—as identified by a survey of Stanford undergraduate students—who prioritize a project&#39;s mission ahead of building their own skills or compensation.</p><p> The debate over outsourcing is not new. Among the many known benefits of outsourcing is that contractors can be more easily held to account and fired when underperforming. When it comes to the US government, however, insourcing all outsourced labor would expand the civil-service workforce from today&#39;s three million people to about 10 million. Moving in that direction would be a political issue of consequence.</p><p> But Ms. Pahlka is onto something. Before Congress created the Office of the President in 1939, for example, a president had but a handful of advisers and personal staff. Today that one small office, among the dozens of administrative agencies, has a $1.5 billion budget and more than 3,000 employees (only a few of which require Senate approval). The world and the economy are bigger now, but bureaucratic expansion has been incommensurate in scale, complexity and authority.</p><p> Ms. Pahlka&#39;s book is a cri de coeur for better “product delivery” from the now massive labyrinth of government services. Count me among those who believe the artificial-intelligence revolution could unlock some bureaucratic transparency and superior service delivery. But whether that will happen, or whether the bog will assimilate yet another technological revolution, is a matter of politics, not process.</p><p> <em>Mr. Mills, a senior fellow at the Manhattan Institute, is a partner at Montrose Lane, an energy-tech venture fund, and the author of “The Cloud Revolution.”</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 22:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/recoding-america-review-a-tale-of-the-tape-449e8b3c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/recoding-america-review-a-tale-of-the-tape-449e8b3c<category> Books</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>books</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Santa Fe Opera Reviews: ‘Orfeo,’ ‘Pelléas et Mélisande,’ ‘Rusalka,’ ‘The Flying Dutchman’ and ‘Tosca’]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> In this year&#39;s festival, Monteverdi&#39;s myth about lost lovers in the underworld takes the stage; Debussy&#39;s Symbolist story finds orchestral triumph; Dvořák&#39;s fairy tale takes a Freudian turn; and more. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590138142555787492"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831075?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Luke Harnish, Rolando Villazón, Lauren Snouffer, Luke Elmer and Le Bu</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Curtis Brown </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12165777042486313942804590138142555787492"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Heidi Waleson</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 8, 2023 5:42 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/santa-fe-opera-reviews-orfeo-pelleas-et-melisande-rusalka-the-flying-dutchman-and-tosca-90e417bc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <em>Santa Fe, NM</em></p><p> This summer, the Santa Fe Opera presented Monteverdi&#39;s <strong>“Orfeo”</strong> with a new orchestration by Nico Muhly. “Orfeo” (1607), one of the earliest operas, is typically performed with period instruments; Mr. Muhly&#39;s resourceful version captured the tang and transparency of those instruments with the tools of a modern opera orchestra. His selection of sonorities—such as low winds and harp for continuo; a single violin for poignant moments; celesta and piano for color—always fit the moment, supported the vocal line, and never slipped into overblown Romanticism. I missed only the harsh rasp of the regal, the period organ that accompanies the character Caronte. As led by Harry Bicket, the company&#39;s music director and an expert in early repertoire, “Orfeo” retained its 17th-century impulse in a new guise.</p><p> As Orfeo, Rolando Villazón was less successful. The tenor&#39;s voice has lowered and darkened in recent years, fitting the role&#39;s baritone tessitura, but his timbre is harsh and barky. Orfeo&#39;s music is supposed to enchant; we got histrionics instead. Lauren Snouffer had a lovely, floating sound as La Musica, who introduces the story, and Speranza, who escorts Orfeo to the portal of the Underworld; Paula Murrihy (La Messaggera) and Blake Denson (Plutone) were also standouts.</p><p> The thoughtful production—directed by Yuval Sharon, with a visual environment by Alex Schweder and Matthew Johnson, and lighting by Yuki Nakase Link—had an ingenious solution to the living world/underworld transition. The shepherds&#39; chorus cavorted on and around a green half-globe. Then the globe gradually lifted, swaths of fabric unfurled beneath it, and Orfeo sang his plea to Caronte while suspended from a harness in the gloom. The gods seemed more powerful because they were invisible; the denizens of the very dark underworld had chic lighted headdresses (Carlos J Soto did the costumes). </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831064?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Huw Montague Rendall and Samantha Hankey in &#39;Pelléas et Mélisande&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Curtis Brown</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In the production of Debussy&#39;s <strong>“Pelléas et Mélisande”</strong> by Netia Jones (director; scenic, costume and projection designer), the subtext involving the toxic clash of modernity and nature didn&#39;t read clearly enough. This Symbolist story was set in what appeared to be a dark basement, reached by a pair of spiral staircases, with a large revolving terrarium that also served as a bed. In the first half of the opera, its grass was green; in the second, it was wilted and yellow. A stream ran along the front edge of the stage; the three principal characters, mystifyingly, had doubles who acted out their scenes upstage. Arkel, Golaud and Mélisande all received oxygen when they were ill or wounded; there were projections of computer code, scientific diagrams, and plumbing pipes; even the images of water and trees were gloomy.</p><p> Musically, however, it was a triumph. Mr. Bicket brought marked clarity to the orchestra, reflecting the characters&#39; unspoken emotions through sonic detail rather than indulging in a misty, nonspecific wash of sound. Zachary Nelson was splendid as the tormented Golaud, his velvety baritone turning desperate as he tried unsuccessfully to find out the truth. As Mélisande, Samantha Hankey&#39;s rich, bright mezzo made her more human than fey; Huw Montague Rendall was arresting in Pelléas&#39;s awakening of feeling for her. Raymond Aceto was affecting as Arkel, the king with no power; as Geneviève, Susan Graham&#39;s mezzo has lost luster, but she looked great in the watery green silk gown that seemed to symbolize the family&#39;s last connection to the natural world. Treble Kai Edgar was a strong Yniold. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831068?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ailyn Pérez in &#39;Rusalka&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Curtis Brown</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> David Pountney&#39;s production of Dvořák&#39;s fairy tale <strong>“Rusalka”</strong> also required advance information for full comprehension. But even without that, it was theatrically clearer than “Pelléas.” Set in a Viennese psychiatric hospital, circa 1900, it explored water nymph Rusalka&#39;s yearning for a human form and soul through a Freudian lens—the violent and confusing sexual transition from childhood to adulthood. The intriguing set (Leslie Travers) went from an orderly white room of closets and drawers to the Prince&#39;s palace, in which glass display cases housed his other female conquests. For Act 3, when everything has fallen apart for both the Prince and Rusalka, the cases were empty and chaotically tilted. Marie-Jeanne Lecca&#39;s Victorian costumes underlined the power of the adult women who control everything: The witch Ježibaba wore a corseted black gown, and a red riding habit, complete with tall boots and a riding crop, gave the Foreign Princess a dominatrix vibe.</p><p> The singers brought out the complexity of the characters beyond their fairy-tale identities. Ailyn Pérez was a passionate Rusalka, especially forceful in Act 3, as she asks the Prince why he betrayed her. Raehann Bryce-Davis brought a big sound and almost comical vanity to Ježibaba; Robert Watson made the Prince, for all his tenorial bluster, a weak man; and as Vodník, James Creswell—who had excellent diction—could only threaten vengeance on those who hurt his daughter, as he was trapped in a wheelchair. Mary Elizabeth Williams&#39;s harsh timbre felt right for the imperious Foreign Princess. Conductor Lidiya Yankovskaya captured the score&#39;s jaunty folk-tinged sections along with its sweep and lyricism. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831061?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Morris Robinson and chorus in &#39;The Flying Dutchman&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Curtis Brown</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> For the most part, the company orchestra sounded much more polished this season than it has in recent years, with the exception of Wagner&#39;s <strong>“The Flying Dutchman.”</strong> Conducted by Thomas Guggeis, it was raucously loud throughout, with no expressive subtleties. The principal singers, all substantial Wagnerians boasting excellent range, breath control and volume, seemed to be trying to match the orchestra for sheer decibel level. As the Dutchman, Nicholas Brownlee sounded thrillingly savage as he launched his opening aria, “Die Frist ist um,” but it quickly became assaultive rather than exciting. Morris Robinson (Daland), Elza van den Heever (Senta) and Chad Shelton (Erik) were similarly afflicted. Only Bille Bruley (the Steersman) escaped that fate—his ballad is brief. “Dutchman” needs more than a little bel canto spirit; there was none to be had here.</p><p> David Alden&#39;s ugly, updated production matched the hard-edge musicianship. Paul Steinberg&#39;s set appeared to be built of shipping containers; the women&#39;s chorus in the Spinning Song were working in some sort of industrial plant, dressed in protective gear (Constance Hoffman did the costumes) and moving like automatons. Other chorus scenes were chaotic in addition to being earsplitting, with sailors rolling around the stage. The Act 3 party, in which the sailors and the women try to awaken the Dutchman&#39;s crew, was a bacchanal; strangely, everyone was facing away from the Dutchman&#39;s barely visible ship (Maxine Braham was credited with choreography). Direction of character scenes was minimal to nonexistent. The most entertaining moments involved some zombies who periodically carted the Dutchman&#39;s treasure on and off the stage. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831058?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Leah Hawkins in &#39;Tosca&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Curtis Brown</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Puccini&#39;s <strong>“Tosca”</strong> was also hard to take. Designer Ashley Martin-Davis&#39;s De Chirico-inspired sets, sensitively lighted by Allen Hahn, were fine, but his 1930s diva costumes did not flatter Leah Hawkins in the title role, and Keith Warner&#39;s directing made Tosca a vain egotist without vulnerability and Scarpia (Reginald Smith Jr.) a leering, eye-rolling sex maniac. Joshua Guerrero&#39;s Cavaradossi was comparatively unobjectionable; his “E lucevan le stelle” was the evening&#39;s sole musical high point. John Fiore&#39;s conducting—ploddingly slow in Act 1, slightly more buoyant in Acts 2 and 3—reflected the production&#39;s overall confusion. The season runs through Aug. 26.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -多发性硬化症。 Waleson writes on opera for the Journal and is the author of “Mad Scenes and Exit Arias: The Death of the New York City Opera and the Future of Opera in America” (Metropolitan).</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 21:42:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/santa-fe-opera-reviews-orfeo-pelleas-et-melisande-rusalka-the-flying-dutchman-and-tosca-90e417bc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/santa-fe-opera-reviews-orfeo-pelleas-et-melisande-rusalka-the-flying-dutchman-and-tosca-90e417bc<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>Opera</category><category> Theater</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>opera</category><category> theater</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Strange Planet’ Review: Alien Characters, Human World]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Based on Nathan W. Pyle&#39;s wildly successful online comic strip and co-created by Dan Harmon of &#39;Rick and Morty,&#39; this adult animated series on Apple TV+ brings to life a quirky alternate society very similar to our own. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590136293366557582"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830585?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A scene from &#39;Strange Planet&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: AppleTV+ </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590136293366557582"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">John Anderson</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 8, 2023 5:40 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/strange-planet-review-alien-characters-human-world-nathan-pyle-dan-harmon-apple-tv-586b1510"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> To paraphrase another famous comic strip, we have met the strangers of “Strange Planet,” and they are us. That, as becomes abundantly clear, is the Jupiter-size joke in Nathan W. Pyle&#39;s webcomic-cum-series on Apple TV+. The more immediate, Mars-equivalent gag is the translation of very earthy reality into absurdist techno-speak: Parents are “life-givers”; years are “revolutions”; unwanted cilantro in your “swaddled mush” is “soap leaf.” You may find your mouth stones on edge before episode 3, and it won&#39;t be from too much jitter liquid. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4></h4><p> <strong>Strange Planet</strong></p><p> <em>Wednesday, Apple TV+</em> </p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> More Television Reviews</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-lost-flowers-of-alice-hart-review-thorny-drama-on-the-australian-prairie-781af5e8?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;The Lost Flowers of Alice Hart&#39; Review: Thorny Drama on the Australian Prairie</a> <span class="date">August 3, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-wild-sides-review-survival-of-the-fiercest-a683a104?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;The Wild Sides&#39; Review: Survival of the Fiercest</a> <span class="date">August 3, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/poisoned-the-dirty-truth-about-your-food-review-netflix-farm-to-table-to-hospital-9444a103?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;Poisoned: The Dirty Truth About Your Food&#39; Review: Farm to Table to Hospital</a> <span class="date">August 1, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-big-nailed-it-baking-challenge-review-netflix-nicole-byer-376b7e62?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">&#39;The Big “Nailed It!” Baking Challenge&#39; Review: Cakes and Chaos</a> <span class="date">August 1, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> On the other hand, “Strange Planet” is an exceedingly low-key, gently amusing offering that&#39;s a far cry from the screamingly conventional anime of the popular “One Piece” or some of the needlessly edgy entries on Adult Swim. There is a place for grown-up animation amid the vast plastic-trash island of an oceanic medium and, besides, “Strange Planet” has a back story that may be more familiar to some than the cartoon itself: Mr. Pyle&#39;s 2019 webcomic on Instagram and his follow-up books were sensations, until a 2017 tweet from Mr. Pyle came to light, one that expressed measured support for the antiabortion March for Life. At that point, he became the target of an abortion-rights backlash, aka the “milkshake duck” internet phenomenon (I had to look it up). Mr. Pyle didn&#39;t apologize and he wasn&#39;t canceled, not judging by the arrival of this 10-episode series created by the cartoonist with Dan Harmon (“Rick and Morty”). So, happy endings.</p><p> There are many of those in “Strange Planet,” the point of it being simple moral lessons—about kindness, or pets—and its shtick being about a view of contemporary human life (“existence”) as if it were being lived in a parallel society, one in which everyone looks like an upside-down periwinkle teardrop and no one has a name; the elderly look like baby-blue raisins. The voice artists include Tunde Adebimpe (“Rachel Getting Married”), Demi Adejuyigbe (“The Amber Ruffin Show”), Lori Tan Chinn (“Awkwafina Is Nora From Queens”), Danny Pudi (“Community”) and Hannah Einbinder (“Hacks”). But who does whom is a bit of a mystery.</p><p> The motion-picture adaptation of a comic strip is certainly nothing new, but some cartoons are more vulnerable than others to having their irony lost in translation or their humor transformed altogether (“Peanuts” comes to mind, as does “Fritz the Cat”). The wry simplicity of “Strange Planet,” in its single frames or quadrants, strains when asked to support a 20-odd-minute premise. But it also becomes a different animal, exploring, say, the invention of air travel and its effect on the mind of “beings,” as the whole race is called. (“I&#39;d love some tiny snacks!” says one, upon taking to the commercial air, where tiny snacks abound.) “Is mild poison available?” a passenger asks, to which a flight attendant replies “Yes, if you can prove you&#39;ve existed long enough.” Documents are produced, along with some laughs, which might be more raucous were a viewer under the influence of some mild poison.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> -先生。 Anderson is the Journal&#39;s TV critic.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 21:40:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/strange-planet-review-alien-characters-human-world-nathan-pyle-dan-harmon-apple-tv-586b1510</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/strange-planet-review-alien-characters-human-world-nathan-pyle-dan-harmon-apple-tv-586b1510<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Television/Radio</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>电视</category><category>收音机</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Best Biopics of the 21st Century—So Far]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> From movies about figure skaters and musicians to Christopher Nolan&#39;s recent blockbuster about the father of the atom bomb and much, much more. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590136662294576850"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11667163785710763363504590136662294576850"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">WSJ Arts in Review Staff</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 8, 2023 5:36 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-best-biopics-of-the-21st-century-oppenheimer-ef971e66"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> As franchises ebb and flow, biographical films remain a staple of cinema. Here are 15 of the greatest biopics of the recent past, according to the Wall Street Journal&#39;s film critics. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB109900504601359169"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831682?width=639&amp;height=1048" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">WSJ</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB109900504601359169?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Ray (2004)</a></h4><p> In the pantheon of popular music, Ray Charles&#39;s voice, like Louis Armstrong&#39;s cornet, is an instrument of heroic power. Taylor Hackford&#39;s biographical film “Ray” synchs Jamie Foxx&#39;s on-screen singing to classic recordings of that voice with a precision that&#39;s entirely convincing. What&#39;s more, Mr. Foxx bears a striking physical resemblance to his subject. (His speaking voice fits perfectly too.) Yet any biopic—a venerable, often clumsy category—must stand or fall on spiritual resemblance, and Mr. Foxx conveys that essential quality at a level of intensity that must be heard, seen and felt to be believed. Beyond the halogen smile and familiar glee, beyond the sideways bobbleheadedness and the teetering gait, this performance stands as a rich dramatic counterpart to the great music. Rather than impersonation, or an earnest effort to fill big shoes, it&#39;s a kind of habitation.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB109900504601359169?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB112803130372656151"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831671?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">SONY PICTURES/EVERETT COLLECTION</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB112803130372656151?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Capote (2005)</a></h4><p> In the course of “Capote,” Bennett Miller&#39;s remarkable film about Truman Capote and the writing of his groundbreaking nonfiction novel “In Cold Blood,” the camera lingers for a moment over a photograph of the real Capote on the dust jacket of his first novel, “Other Voices, Other Rooms.” It&#39;s Harold Halma&#39;s famous shot of him looking boyish and ethereal as he leans on the back of a chair, yet it seems perfectly consonant, in the context of the film, with Philip Seymour Hoffman&#39;s portrayal of the writer as a man approaching middle age. What Mr. Hoffman has done here borders on the miraculous. Beyond the effete speech and the extravagant mannerisms, all of which ring resoundingly true, this formidable actor has nailed the essence of his equally formidable subject —the intelligence and charm, the consuming narcissism, the steely regard, the truculent, tough-as-nails ambition to make his mark. What&#39;s more, the film deserves him. It&#39;s the most thoughtful mainstream feature ever made about writers and writing.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB112803130372656151?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122781826191262117"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831669?width=700&amp;height=465" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">Focus Features</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122781826191262117?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Milk (2008)</a></h4><p> Gus Van Sant&#39;s “Milk,” with Sean Penn as Harvey Milk, opens on the late gay activist and San Francisco supervisor dictating into a tape recorder. The year is 1978, and the words are taken from a tape, full of foreboding, that Milk did in fact dictate shortly before he, and the city&#39;s mayor, George Moscone, were shot to death by a former supervisor, Dan White. The sequence is an enthralling example of minimalist acting—we&#39;re pulled in by a voice hardly raised above a murmur, and by barely varied tones that somehow convey deep feeling. And we stay in through the all-too-brief span of Milk&#39;s career, from his start as a community organizer to his victory as the nation&#39;s first openly gay candidate to win a major political office. More than acting, though, Penn&#39;s performance is a marvelous act of empathy in a movie that, for all its surprisingly conventional style, measures up to its stirring subject.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB122781826191262117?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Read the review (second in the column)</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324894104578106610813833952"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831652?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">Dreamworks</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324894104578106610813833952?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Lincoln (2012)</a></h4><p> The carnage of war provides a preface to Steven Spielberg&#39;s “Lincoln,” just as it did in “Saving Private Ryan.” But this is carnage of a sort so old—a war in which fists, strangulations and stompings supplement bullets and bayonets—that its depiction on screen seems new. Mr. Spielberg&#39;s remarkable film seems old and new too: genuinely old in its beautifully rendered settings and costumes; genuinely new in its placement of our 16th president, portrayed in eccentric glory by Daniel Day-Lewis, within the politics of his day. ( Tony Kushner&#39;s electrifying screenplay was partly based on Doris Kearns Goodwin&#39;s “Team of Rivals: The Political Genius of Abraham Lincoln. ”)</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324894104578106610813833952?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Read the review (second in the column)</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-theory-of-everything-review-uniting-love-and-quantum-mechanics-1415303526"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831644?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">Liam Daniel/Associated Press</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-theory-of-everything-review-uniting-love-and-quantum-mechanics-1415303526?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">The Theory of Everything (2014)</a></h4><p> What a week for science. “The Theory of Everything,” with Eddie Redmayne starring—brilliantly—as the cosmologist Stephen Hawking, ticks off many of the same concepts we encounter in “Interstellar”: black holes, the life and death of stars, a space-time singularity, quantum mechanics and relativity as the two pillars of modern physics. And, as in “Interstellar,” we can&#39;t really understand what&#39;s being discussed unless we are, as I am not, literate in math and theoretical physics. In this case, though, what we don&#39;t know doesn&#39;t trouble us. James Marsh&#39;s movie, which co-stars Felicity Jones as Jane Hawking,</p> the celebrated physicist&#39;s wife, is a biographical love story that doesn&#39;t depend on science to shape the plot—it&#39;s rich in emotional intelligence.<p></p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-theory-of-everything-review-uniting-love-and-quantum-mechanics-1415303526?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-sniper-review-the-good-the-terse-and-the-tragic-1419443121"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831688?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">Warner Bros./Everett Collection</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-sniper-review-the-good-the-terse-and-the-tragic-1419443121?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">American Sniper (2014)</a></h4><p> One of the most telling moments in Clint Eastwood&#39;s remarkable “American Sniper” comes after Chris Kyle, the real-life US Navy SEAL and Iraq war hero played by Bradley Cooper, has picked off two targets—two human beings—he didn&#39;t want to kill. Without looking away from his gun sight, the sniper reflects, silently and briefly, on what he&#39;s just done. But what, exactly, does the moment tell of Kyle&#39;s feelings? Nothing that can be put into words, and nothing that needs to be at that point. A man of few words, Kyle keeps himself at a safe remove from any feelings that might interfere with his fulfilling his lethal assignment. Mr. Eastwood&#39;s film lets this good and anguished man speak for himself, and discover himself, at his own pace.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-sniper-review-the-good-the-terse-and-the-tragic-1419443121?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hacksaw-ridge-review-saving-grace-in-the-firing-line-1478199740"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831691?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">Lionsgate</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hacksaw-ridge-review-saving-grace-in-the-firing-line-1478199740?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Hacksaw Ridge (2016)</a></h4><p> Impassioned patriotism and religious conviction constitute the core of “Hacksaw Ridge,” a stirring—and surpassingly violent—dramatization of the life of Desmond T. Doss, the first conscientious objector to receive the Medal of Honor. As an unarmed combat medic in World War II, Cpl. Doss saved the lives of at least 75 fellow infantrymen during a horrific battle on the Japanese-held island of Okinawa. He&#39;s played by</p> Andrew Garfield, whose extraordinary performance turns inner torment into ardent resolve, and a desperate heroism seldom seen on screen.<p></p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hacksaw-ridge-review-saving-grace-in-the-firing-line-1478199740?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hidden-figures-review-breaking-barriers-of-space-race-and-gender-1483638262"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831693?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">20TH CENTURY FOX</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hidden-figures-review-breaking-barriers-of-space-race-and-gender-1483638262?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Hidden Figures (2016)</a></h4><p> “Hidden Figures” brings news that keeps you thinking with amazement, “Who knew?” Its larger subject, set in the early 1960s during the height of the Cold War, is a story that had already been told definitively, or so we may have thought, by Tom Wolfe&#39;s “The Right Stuff” and the movie based on his book—Project Mercury and America&#39;s race with the Soviet Union to put a man into space. But who knew that NASA depended, at that pioneering time, on flesh-and-blood mathematicians (they were called computers) to calculate flight trajectories until sufficiently powerful transistor-and-punch-card computers came on line; that many of those gifted people were black women, working together in a segregated unit at NASA&#39;s Langley Research Center in Hampton, Va.; and that one member of the unit played a crucial role in the flight that made John Glenn the first American to orbit the Earth?</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hidden-figures-review-breaking-barriers-of-space-race-and-gender-1483638262?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/i-tonya-review-we-fascinated-1512686394"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831696?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">Neon</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/i-tonya-review-we-fascinated-1512686394?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">I, Tonya (2017)</a></h4><p> Impressive in its own right, “I, Tonya” offers an antidote to those feel-good films about innately noble athletes who manage to triumph over impossible odds. This is a feel-real film, a sharp-witted, tough-minded biopic about Tonya Harding,</p> the 1991 US figure skating champion and two-time Olympian who skated rinks around most of her rivals but never became America&#39;s sweetheart. In the first of many straight-to-the camera, faux-documentary interviews, Tonya, played with dazzling ferocity by Margot Robbie, says “I&#39;m a real person.” That&#39;s never in doubt, even when the movie trips or falters. She is really talented and really wounded, a foul-mouthed heroine driven by hurt and a simmering anger that can rise to focused fury.<p></p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/i-tonya-review-we-fascinated-1512686394?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-man-review-sticking-an-epic-landing-1539283178"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831701?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">UNIVERSAL STUDIOS</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-man-review-sticking-an-epic-landing-1539283178?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">First Man (2018)</a></h4><p> The radical notion behind Damien Chazelle&#39;s remarkable “First Man” is this: Tell the story of mankind&#39;s boldest adventure thus far, the Apollo 11 mission that reached the moon nearly a half-century ago, but tell it through a taciturn, emotionally closed-off hero, Neil Armstrong, the first man to walk on the lunar surface. And pay close attention to this man&#39;s state of mind and spirit, as well as to the mission&#39;s spectacular success, so the story is equally about what it means to be flesh-and-blood human while walking on Earth.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-man-review-sticking-an-epic-landing-1539283178?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rocketman-review-a-biopic-blasts-off-11558385211"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831704?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">DAVID APPLEBY/PARAMOUNT PICTURES/ASSOCIATED PRESS</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rocketman-review-a-biopic-blasts-off-11558385211?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Rocketman (2019)</a></h4><p> Much of the bountiful pleasure of “Rocketman,” a jukebox musical about the genesis, emergence and turbulent triumph of a self-creation named Elton John, comes from the film&#39;s delight in embellishing its subject&#39;s embellishments, gilding its legendary lily. The events of his breakthrough years are heightened with fantasy sequences that amount to a swirling, semi-surreal remix of his career and inner life. The colors are stunning, the settings are striking and the energy is irresistible, even if the pop psychologizing is pretty glib. Yet this gorgeously preposterous phantasmagoria wouldn&#39;t hold us as it does if it weren&#39;t based on something real and true, and two realities operate in tandem—the songs, whose beauty and power have only been amplified by the passage of time; and a starring performance of dazzling audacity by Taron Egerton, who evokes the great man without falling back on mimicry. Mr. Egerton&#39;s singing and dancing, as well as his nuanced acting, are entirely convincing, yet a distinctive creation of his own.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rocketman-review-a-biopic-blasts-off-11558385211?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-beautiful-day-in-the-neighborhood-review-healing-arts-11574373682"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831708?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">Sony Pictures</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-beautiful-day-in-the-neighborhood-review-healing-arts-11574373682?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">A Beautiful Day in the Neighborhood (2019)</a></h4><p> Tom Hanks is Fred Rogers, the beloved TV host, in “A Beautiful Day in the Neighborhood.” It&#39;s a perfect piece of casting for an inspirational fable in which forgiveness opens the way to a state of grace. Fred, turning his gifts for kindness and empathy on a cynical magazine writer who has come to profile him, helps the man heal his angry heart. The story plays out in a pair of realms that sometimes overlap or merge—the real world of the journalist and the fantasy world of “Mister Rogers&#39; Neighborhood,” where life lessons for kids are dispensed with gentle eloquence at an unhurried pace. Given the nature of the production—it was made for grownups, not children, in an era when life moves much faster than it did in Mr. Rogers&#39;s day—sticky sweetness threatens at every turn, along with naked contrivance. Yet the movie bets on goodness, and wins.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-beautiful-day-in-the-neighborhood-review-healing-arts-11574373682?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-interactiveLink"><div class="image-container"> <a class="interactive-link" href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-hidden-life-review-mournful-memorable-and-emotionally-exhilarating-11576185486"><img width="16" height="10" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831711?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><span class="image-interactive-icon">
            </span></a></div><div class="wsj-article-caption"><span class="wsj-article-credit">Twentieth Century Fox</span></div></div></div><h4> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-hidden-life-review-mournful-memorable-and-emotionally-exhilarating-11576185486?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">A Hidden Life (2019)</a></h4><p> Terrence Malick has spent the past decade or so in motion, spinning away from what was the already untraditional storytelling of his early masterpieces (“Badlands,” “Days of Heaven”), and into a space of purely visual intentions: Try as one might to locate a conventional narrative in 2015&#39;s “Knight of Cups,” for instance, the film was really about architecture.</p><p> What Mr. Malick has been concerned with consistently, though, is the individual&#39;s place in the cosmos; whether his or her philosophy matters; whether there is a God, and if so what we owe him. And what, if anything, he owes us. With “A Hidden Life” and the story of Franz Jägerstätter, the director has found the ideal vehicle for his cosmic inquiries, and has created a film that is mournful, memorable and emotionally exhilarating.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-hidden-life-review-mournful-memorable-and-emotionally-exhilarating-11576185486?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">阅读评论</a></p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/putin-and-the-presidents-review-pbs-frontline-bill-clinton-trump-biden-11674771209?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"></a></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          largerule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
